@page "/impact"

<section class="impact-hero">
    <h1>Our Impact</h1>
    <p>
        Ripple exists to address food insecurity in the Chicagoland area through sustainable, 
        community‑centered aquaponics. Our work focuses on increasing access to fresh food, 
        strengthening local partnerships, and building long‑term resilience in neighborhoods 
        facing food deserts.
    </p>
</section>

<section class="impact-section">
    <h2>Food Insecurity in Chicago</h2>
    <p>
        More than one‑third of Chicago‑area households struggle to afford basic living costs, 
        putting them at serious risk of hunger. Many neighborhoods lack reliable access to fresh 
        produce, and rising grocery prices, housing costs, and reductions in SNAP benefits make 
        the problem worse.
    </p>
    <p>
        Ripple aims to close this gap by producing fresh, nutrient‑dense food year‑round — right 
        where it’s needed most.
    </p>
</section>

<section class="impact-section">
    <h2>How Ripple Helps</h2>

    <div class="impact-grid">
        <div class="impact-card">
            <h3>Year‑Round Food Production</h3>
            <p>
                Our aquaponics system grows leafy greens and tilapia continuously, unaffected by 
                weather or season.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="impact-card">
            <h3>Local Distribution</h3>
            <p>
                We partner with food pantries, shelters, and community organizations to deliver 
                produce and fish directly to families who need it most.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="impact-card">
            <h3>Sustainable Farming</h3>
            <p>
                Aquaponics uses up to <strong>90% less water</strong>, requires no soil, and 
                minimizes chemical inputs.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="impact-card">
            <h3>Community Engagement</h3>
            <p>
                Volunteers, students, and local residents participate in planting, harvesting, 
                packaging, and outreach.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="impact-card">
            <h3>Education & Research</h3>
            <p>
                Our research area supports innovation in aquaponics and helps us share knowledge 
                with the broader community.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="impact-section">
    <h2>Environmental Impact</h2>
    <p>
        Aquaponics reduces environmental strain by conserving water, reducing land use, lowering 
        carbon footprint, minimizing chemical inputs, and supporting biodiversity. Ripple’s facility 
        also incorporates skylights, efficient LED lighting, and energy‑saving design choices.
    </p>
</section>

<section class="impact-section">
    <h2>Building a More Resilient Future</h2>
    <p>
        Aquaponics is not a full replacement for traditional agriculture — but it is a powerful 
        supplement. By producing food locally, sustainably, and predictably, Ripple helps 
        communities become more resilient to climate change, supply chain disruptions, rising 
        food costs, and seasonal shortages.
    </p>
</section>
